I have used this app for years and it works great. It is very dependable and if you just follow the process to get it activated, everything works nicely.  I would recommend two improvements to future versions:  1. If stopped at a location for more than say 10 minutes, the app should suspend broadcasting to save battery on the cell phone.  2. If the app had a "home location" and a target location set, then upon arriving to home, or a targeted destination, then the broadcast should turn off, saving battery time.  These two features would just make a great app that much better!

A simply brilliant App! Works as advertised. I applied for a passcode before buying/installing the app as recommended and in fewer than 36 hours my passcode was emailed to me on a Sunday morning completely hassle free.  Installation and set-up of the app took five minutes and it worked flawlessly on the first try. It doesn't get any better/easier than that!  Only small hitch was the APRS-SI passcode application form does not work with Microsoft Edge so I had to switch to Chrome. After that, the transaction was flawless .  Nicely done, easy to use, and well worth the small fee to support the developer.  73 and thanks again. EDIT: Tested Tracking - works great, better than using HT.

This app is worth every penny and a whole lot more. Over the last 24 hours, I've tested this both on and off road: it hasn't missed a beat. Unlike sharing your location on Google Maps, APRSdroid doesn't throw a fit if you're not on a road or other byway. It merely continues to report your GPS coordinates, speed and direction. Unlike other APRS apps, it's stable and recovers quickly from blips in internet connection. As you might have guessed, I recommend this app!

This app works very well for any radio amateur who is interested in being part of the APRS system. It is easy to use, has quite a few options in the preferences/settings section. My primary interest is in using it for sending position reports as part of the local Skywarn volunteer group. The uses of this are as varied as there are radio amateurs out there. Well worth the small fee that is charged for its use.

Truly a no-brainer purchase, and worth every cent of the applications modest cost.  Download the free APK first if you have any doubts.  <rant> Ignore the negative reviews.  Yes, you need to wait for approval to use IP based position updates - yes, it may even take a while.  Big deal, get over it. Using this with a Mobilinkd Bluetooth TNC with my Droid Bionic and a VX-7. Easy to setup if you have done any APRS before. Otherwise, look at Bob Bruniga's website and learn the basics first.  One reviewer complained that this app will flood APRS with beacons since it does not listen. This not true. With the Mobilnkd TNC, a received signal blocks transmission.With the Internet only beacon, the packets only appear on the APRS port of the web and does not transmit an RF signal so there is no packet flood on your local Igate, only a plot on aprs.fi. I think the internet can handle your beacons.  One other caution, APRS is not intended to be a real time vehicle tracker. There are other devices and apps to track your teenager or whatever. Using a very short interval for beaconing will flood the system with too many packets. Smart Beacon, which this software supports, is your and the entire packet communiy's friend. Use it.  BTW, getting a pass code was very simple and quick.

replyContent: The APRS-IS passcode can be requested online, just tap "Request Passcode" in the app preferences. Because a manual check is required, this may take some days. Feel free to request a refund via Google Play if the app does not meet your expectations. 73

content: APRSdroid is a good way to send and receive APRS data when you don't have an APRS capable radio available. I carried my phone (S3) to the Dayton hamvention and it worked well under those high traffic conditions. I saw several others on the air at that time using the app.The software needs to provide speed and direction data for mobile and weather info from the APRS weather stations.
Works well

I have this app installed on my cellphone. I find the app to be very useful in locating nearby HAM repeaters.  The Repeaters with APRS respond with a report stating their frequencies and how far away they are.  Also, a Google map shows current location and location tracks for the previous 24 hours.  APRSdroid works well as an alternate to report position when the GPS-TT4-2m rig is not hitting the repeater well.  I've also found it useful as a tool to run side-by side a Microtrak-RTG to determine where all the APRS (and cell) coverage holes are.    I am ordering the Byonics Bluetooth adapter for my TT4 and will see if 2m rig-TT4 w bluetooth-Android tablet or cellphone running APRSdroid can work well as an iGateway.  Since Android tablets come with host-USB connectors, it would be nice if APRSdroid could talk directly to a KISS TNC.

The app was great when I was using it over TCP/IP only. I got a byonics bluetooth adapter and switched the app to bluetooth TNC mode. The app crashed immediately. Now even though I switched the app back to use TCP/IP it still tries to connect to bluetooth TNC and immediately crashes.
replyContent: Please contact us via e-mail if you encounter crashes. That way, we can find the problem together and create a fix for it.

content: I bought it 4 days ago. Still no passcode. Its a scam. Hope you are not in a hurry to use it. You will have to beg for your passcode. That takes about 2 weeks. What a rip off.
replyContent: We are really sorry that the passcode validation takes several days to accomplish. It is a manual process to prevent abuse of your callsign on the APRS-IS network, and it is performed by volunteers.
